<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a 529 college savings plan?", answer: "A 529 plan is a tax-advantaged investment account designed for education expenses. Contributions grow tax-free, and withdrawals for qualified education expenses like tuition, room and board, books, and even K-12 tuition up to $10,000 per year are also tax-free. Most states offer additional state income tax deductions or credits for contributions." },
  { question: "How much should I save monthly for college?", answer: "To cover the average cost of a 4-year public university, saving $300-500 per month starting from birth should put you on track. For private universities, aim for $500-800 per month. Starting later requires higher monthly contributions due to less time for compound growth. Even small amounts help, and any savings reduce future student loan borrowing." },
  { question: "What are the tax benefits of a 529 plan?", answer: "529 plans offer triple tax benefits: contributions may be deductible on your state income tax, investment growth is tax-deferred, and qualified withdrawals are completely tax-free at both federal and state levels. Over 30 states offer a full or partial state income tax deduction for contributions, saving families hundreds or thousands per year." },
  { question: "What happens if my child does not go to college?", answer: "You can change the beneficiary to another family member, including siblings, cousins, nieces, nephews, or even yourself. Unused 529 funds can also be rolled into a Roth IRA for the beneficiary (up to $35,000 lifetime, subject to annual contribution limits, and the 529 must be open for 15+ years). Non-qualified withdrawals face income tax and a 10% penalty on earnings only." },
  { question: "Can I use 529 funds for graduate school?", answer: "Yes, 529 plans can be used for any accredited post-secondary institution including graduate school, medical school, law school, MBA programs, and professional certifications. Qualified expenses include tuition, required fees, books, supplies, equipment, and room and board for students enrolled at least half-time." }
]) %>

